ce:section.ce:para:
For each trial, Fe3O4/CDs@MIPs were prepared with varying amounts of Fe3O4 nanoparticles, while keeping the concentrations of ZIF-8, N, S-CDs, and other components constant. The fluorescence quenching efficiency of each resulting sensor was tested in the presence of p-Hydroxybenzoic acid (
                           Fig. S1
                        ). The results showed that the fluorescence quenching efficiency reached its peak when 40 mg of Fe3O4 nanoparticles were incorporated into the sensor structure. This concentration was identified as optimal, providing a balance between sufficient magnetic functionality and maintaining the structural integrity necessary for effective fluorescence detection. The 40 mg Fe3O4 concentration ensured efficient target binding, leading to enhanced fluorescence response and improved sensor sensitivity. Furthermore, this amount contributed to the sensor's high specificity for p-Hydroxybenzoic acid, suggesting that it is the ideal concentration for maximizing both the magnetic enrichment and fluorescence detection capabilities of the sensor. In addition, due to the addition of Fe3O4, when the magnet approached, Fe3O4/CDs@MIPs could achieve rapid separation (
                           Fig. S2
                        ).

To assess the accuracy and practical applicability of the Fe3O4/CDs@MIPs sensor, spike recovery experiments were conducted on urine samples collected from gastric cancer patients and healthy individuals. The results revealed that the concentrations of p-Hydroxybenzoic acid in the urine samples from gastric cancer patients 1 and 2 were 13.66 μmol/L and 14.75 μmol/L, respectively (
                        Table 1

                        ). In contrast, the concentrations in the urine samples from healthy individuals 1, 2, and 3 were significantly lower, at 1.00 μmol/L, not detected, and 2.52 μmol/L, respectively. The calculated recovery rates ranged from 95.00 % to 106.67 %, with relative standard deviations (RSDs) between 0.76 % and 2.80 %.
